England"},"nl":{"about 1412–1445":"circa 1412–1445","1401–1452":"1401–1452","1402–Male":"1402–Overleden","1403–Male":"1403–Overleden","1404–Female":"1404–Overleden","1412–1445":"1412–1445","1411–1429":"1411–1429","1430–1489":"1430–1489","1370–1404":"1370–1404","1386–1404":"1386–1404","1370":"1370","Aft 1429":"na 1429","1404":"1404","1403":"1403","1402":"1402","1445":"1445","1489":"1489","1412":"1412","1401":"1401","1411":"1411","1430":"1430","1386":"1386","1452":"1452","about 1412":"circa 1412","1429":"1429","Brockton, Stanton Long, Shropshire, England, United Kingdom":"Stanton Long, Shropshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Brockton, Shropshire, England":"Brockton, Shropshire, England","Hogsthorpe, Lincolnshire, England":"Hogsthorpe, Lincolnshire, England"},"en":{"about 1412–1445":"about 1412–1445","1401–1452":"1401–1452","1402–Male":"1402–Deceased","1403–Male":"1403–Deceased","1404–Female":"1404–Deceased","1412–1445":"1412–1445","1411–1429":"1411–1429","1430–1489":"1430–1489","1370–1404":"1370–1404","1386–1404":"1386–1404","1370":"1370","Aft 1429":"after 1429","1404":"1404","1403":"1403","1402":"1402","1445":"1445","1489":"1489","1412":"1412","1401":"1401","1411":"1411","1430":"1430","1386":"1386","1452":"1452","about 1412":"about 1412","1429":"1429","Brockton, Stanton Long, Shropshire, England, United Kingdom":"Stanton Long, Shropshire, England, United Kingdom","Brockton, Shropshire, England":"Brockton, Shropshire, England","Hogsthorpe, Lincolnshire, England":"Hogsthorpe, Lincolnshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Newcomb","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: nickname for a new arrival in a place, from Middle English <i>newe-comen</i>, <i>newe-come</i> ‘newly arrived, recently come’ (Old English <i>nīwe</i> + <i>cumen</i>, <i>cuma</i>). The intrusive <i>-b-</i> is the result of the influence of placenames ending in Old English <i>cumb</i> ‘valley’ (see   Coombe  ). No such placename as <i>Newcombe</i> is actually on record in Britain.","Americanized form of German <b>Neukamm</b>, possibly arising from a misinterpretation of its etymology as <i>neu</i> ‘new’ + <i>Kamm</i> ‘comb’ (see   Neukam  ).","History: According to family tradition, Capt. Andrew Newcomb was born in England in 1618 and died in Boston, MA, in 1686, leaving family who settled both in MA and in Kittery, ME. Among his descendants was the internationally renowned astronomer Simon Newcomb (1835–1909)."],"variants":[{"name":"Coombe","meanings":["English (Devon and Cornwall):","topographic name from Middle English <i>combe</i> (Old English <i>cumb</i>, of Celtic origin) denoting a bowl-shaped valley, or else a habitational name from a place so named. A large number of places in southwestern England, mostly spelled <i>Combe</i>, are named with this word.","nickname from Middle English <i>come</i> (Old English <i>cuma</i>) ‘guest, stranger, newcomer’. Compare   Coombs  ."]},{"name":"Newcombe","meanings":["English (Devon): variant of   Newcomb  .","Possibly an Americanized form of German <b>Neukamm</b> (see   Newcomb   2)."]},{"name":"Newcome","meanings":["English: variant of   Newcomb  .","Probably an Americanized form of German <b>Neukomm</b> or   Neukam  ."]}]},{"name":"Jane","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a feminine form of   John  , from the Old French form <i>Je(h)anne</i>. Since the 17th century it has proved the most popular of the feminine forms of <i>John</i>, ahead of   Joan   and   Jean .  It now also commonly occurs as the second element in combinations such as <i>Sarah-Jane</i>. In Britain it is still one of the most frequent of all girls' names. It is not a royal name, but was borne by the tragic  Lady Jane Grey  (  1537–54 ), who was unwillingly proclaimed queen in  1553 , deposed nine days later, and executed the following year. Seventy years earlier, the name had come into prominence as that of  Jane Shore , mistress of  King Edward IV  and subsequently of  Thomas Grey , 1st Marquess of Dorset, Lady Jane's grandfather. Jane Shore's tribulations in  1483  at the hands of  Richard III , Edward's brother and successor, became the subject of popular ballads and plays, which may well have increased the currency of the name in the 16th century. A 19th-century influence was its use as the name of the central character in  Charlotte Brontë's  novel Jane Eyre (  1847 ). From  1932 to 1959  it was used as the name of a cheerful and scantily clad beauty whose adventures were chronicled in a strip cartoon in the Daily Mirror. It is also borne by the American film stars  Jane Russell  (  1921–2011 ) and  Jane Fonda  (  b. 1937 )."],"variants":[{"name":"Jayne","meanings":["Elaborated spelling of   Jane  , a form popularized no doubt by the American actress  Jayne Mansfield  (  Vera Jayne Palmer ,  1933–67 ) and British ice-dancer  Jayne Torvill  (  b. 1957 )."]},{"name":"Jaine","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Jane ."]},{"name":"Jain","meanings":["Originally a feminine form of   John  , from the Old French form <i>Je(h)anne</i>. Since the 17th century it has proved the most popular of the feminine forms of <i>John</i>, ahead of   Joan   and   Jean .  It now also commonly occurs as the second element in combinations such as <i>Sarah-Jane</i>. In Britain it is still one of the most frequent of all girls' names. It is not a royal name, but was borne by the tragic  Lady Jane Grey  (  1537–54 ), who was unwillingly proclaimed queen in  1553 , deposed nine days later, and executed the following year. Seventy years earlier, the name had come into prominence as that of  Jane Shore , mistress of  King Edward IV  and subsequently of  Thomas Grey , 1st Marquess of Dorset, Lady Jane's grandfather. Jane Shore's tribulations in  1483  at the hands of  Richard III , Edward's brother and successor, became the subject of popular ballads and plays, which may well have increased the currency of the name in the 16th century. A 19th-century influence was its use as the name of the central character in  Charlotte Brontë's  novel Jane Eyre (  1847 ). From  1932 to 1959  it was used as the name of a cheerful and scantily clad beauty whose adventures were chronicled in a strip cartoon in the Daily Mirror. It is also borne by the American film stars  Jane Russell  (  1921–2011 ) and  Jane Fonda  (  b. 1937 )."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Jane Newcomb was born about 1412, in Hogsthorpe, Lincolnshire, England, her father, William Le Newcomen, was 44 and her mother, Margaret Blundeville, was 27. She had at least 1 daughter with William Brocton Jr. She died in 1445, in Brockton, Shropshire, England, at the age of 34."},"et":{"about 1412–1445":"umbes 1412–1445","1401–1452":"1401–1452","1402–Male":"1402–Surnud","1403–Male":"1403–Surnud","1404–Female":"1404–Surnud","1412–1445":"1412–1445","1411–1429":"1411–1429","1430–1489":"1430–1489","1370–1404":"1370–1404","1386–1404":"1386–1404","1370":"1370","Aft 1429":"pärast 1429","1404":"1404","1403":"1403","1402":"1402","1445":"1445","1489":"1489","1412":"1412","1401":"1401","1411":"1411","1430":"1430","1386":"1386","1452":"1452","about 1412":"umbes 1412","1429":"1429","Brockton, Stanton Long, Shropshire, England, United Kingdom":"Stanton Long, Shropshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Brockton, Shropshire, England":"Brockton, Shropshire, England","Hogsthorpe, Lincolnshire, England":"Hogsthorpe, Lincolnshire, England"},"fi":{"about 1412–1445":"noin 1412–1445","1401–1452":"1401–1452","1402–Male":"1402–Kuollut","1403–Male":"1403–Kuollut","1404–Female":"1404–Kuollut","1412–1445":"1412–1445","1411–1429":"1411–1429","1430–1489":"1430–1489","1370–1404":"1370–1404","1386–1404":"1386–1404","1370":"1370","Aft 1429":"1429 jälkeen","1404":"1404","1403":"1403","1402":"1402","1445":"1445","1489":"1489","1412":"1412","1401":"1401","1411":"1411","1430":"1430","1386":"1386","1452":"1452","about 1412":"noin 